   "source": [
    "# Quickstart\n",
    "\n",
    "Once installation is complete you can start running Sarkas. This quickstart guide will walk you through\n",
    "a simple example in order to check that everything is running smoothly.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "## Simulation\n",
    "\n",
    "In Jupyter notebook you can run the following commands"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Using matplotlib backend: Qt5Agg\n",
      "Populating the interactive namespace from numpy and matplotlib\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Import the usual libraries\n",
    "%pylab\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "import os\n",
    "\n",
    "# Import sarkas\n",
    "from sarkas.processes import Simulation, PostProcess\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the file path to the YAML input file\n",
    "example_directory = os.path.join('..',\n",
    "                                 os.path.join('sarkas','examples'))\n",
    "\n",
    "input_file_name = os.path.join(example_directory, 'yocp_cgs_pp.yaml')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can find this notebook in the directory `sarkas/notebooks` that was download with the repository.\n",
    "This example notebook will run a short simulation using the `yocp_cgs_pp.yaml` input file found in the examples directory in `sarkas`.\n",
    "\n",
    "The above commands imported the required libraries and define the file path to our input file. \n",
    "\n",
    "Let's now run the simulation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false
   },

   "source": [
    "# Initialize the Simulation class\n",
    "sim = Simulation(input_file_name)\n",
    "# Setup the simulation's parameters\n",
    "sim.setup(read_yaml=True)\n",
    "# Run the simulation\n",
    "sim.run()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Postprocessing\n",
    "\n",
    "Now that our simulation is complete we need to check if the simulation was physically sound. The first thing to do is to inizialize the `PostProcess` class with the input file name."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Initialize the Postprocessing class\n",
    "postproc = PostProcess(input_file_name)\n",
    "postproc.setup(read_yaml=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next we want to check that the system equilibrated correctly. We do this by calling the `Thermodynamics` class and plot the temperature and energy as a function of time. You should get a plot like this"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1152x648 with 7 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "postproc.therm.setup(postproc.parameters)\n",
    "postproc.therm.temp_energy_plot(postproc, phase='equilibration')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The important thing to check is that the temperature has relaxed to the desired value, _i.e._ the red dashed line.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Next we look at the energy and temperature of the production phase. This is done by the same command as above but changing the `phase` option to `production`. You should get a plot like this"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1152x648 with 7 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "postproc.therm.temp_energy_plot(postproc, phase='production')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You will notice that both the energy and temperature oscillates wildly. This is fine as long as the percentage deviations, in the top plots, are small. You should have a temperature deviations between -2% to ~ 4-5% while energy deviations between -2% and 1%.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "### Observables\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's calculate some physical quantities. The most common observable is the radial distribution function. This is calculated by calling the `RadialDistributionFunction` class within the postprocess. \n",
    "The radial distribution function is partially calculated during the production phase, hence, after initializing the class we will call the `save` function to complete the calculation. Finally we plot it and you should obtain a similar plot"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<AxesSubplot:xlabel='$r/a_{\\\\rm ws}$'>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 10,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 720x504 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Initialize the Pair Distribution Function class\n",
    "plt.style.use('MSUstyle')\n",
    "postproc.rdf.setup(postproc.parameters)\n",
    "postproc.rdf.compute()\n",
    "postproc.rdf.plot(normalization=postproc.parameters.a_ws, xlabel = r'$r/a_{\\rm ws}$')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Things to check in here are: \n",
    "\n",
    "* Does $g(r)$ go to 1 for large $r$ values ?\n",
    "* Is there a peak at $r = ~1.5 a$ ?\n",
    "* Is the height of this peak about ~ 1.4?\n",
    "\n",
    "If the answer to all these question is yes than the simulation was successfull."
   ]
  }
 ],
